Hypertriglyceridemia-induced acute pancreatitis treated with insulin and heparin. A case of hypertriglyceridemia-induced acute pancreatitis that was managed with insulin and heparin is reported.A 39-year-old Hispanic man arrived at the emergency department with complaints of abdominal pain, nausea, and vomiting over one day. A computed tomography scan of the abdomen revealed peripancreatic inflammatory changes surrounding the tail of the pancreas, consistent with pancreatitis. Pertinent laboratory test values on admission were as follows: triglyceride concentration, 5366 mg/dL total cholesterol concentration, 555 mg/dLA 39-year-old man with pancreatitis caused by severe hypertriglyceridemia was treated with a continuous insulin infusion and subcutaneous heparin.